<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-144-168  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 144 168.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  March 27 1989 n410 p3(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>GSA plan targets agency-vendor disputes.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Peterson, Stacey.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The General Services Administration (GSA) plans to mediatedisputes between vendors and agencies.andP;  The plan has drawncriticism from both vendors and agencies because several reviewprocesses are already in place.andP;  Disputes should be handled on theagency level, as is done with the Army's Communications andElectronics Command.andP;  Only 1 percent of federal computerprocurements were disputed, with the government losing just 20percent of the total protests in 1988.andP;  The GSA plans to add 10positions to the group handling disputes, by Apr 1989, and willalso provide guidelines for dealing with dealer protests toagencies.andP;  The new system will be binding on agencies, althoughnot on vendors, and is likely to delay procurements.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. General Services AdministrationGovernment ContractsGovernment RegulationVendorsReviewGovernment AgencyPurchasing Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>